<li id="cite_note-45"><b><a href="#cite_ref-45" title="">^</a></b> <i>Cookbook</i> is now standard in BrE. <a href="http://www.oup.com/oald-bin/web_getald7index1a.pl?nav=on&amp;which_entry=008170%23x1%23x2%23cookbook&amp;selected_word=cookbook&amp;search_word=cookery" class="external autonumber" title="http://www.oup.com/oald-bin/web_getald7index1a.pl?nav=on&amp;which_entry=008170%23x1%23x2%23cookbook&amp;selected_word=cookbook&amp;search_word=cookery" rel="nofollow">[5]</a></li>
<li id="cite_note-46"><b><a href="#cite_ref-46" title="">^</a></b> Crystal states one of the classification problems as
<dl>
<dd>
<dl>
<dd>"We have to allow for words which have at least one [shared] meaning and one or more additional meanings that are specific to either AmE or BrE: an example is caravan, which in the sense of 'group of travellers in the desert' is common to both varieties; but in the sense of 'vehicle towed by a car' it is BrE (=AmE trailer)"</dd>
</dl>
</dd>
</dl>
David Crystal, The Cambridge Encyclopedia of The English Language. 2nd Edition. (Cambridge University Press, 2003)</li>
<li id="cite_note-47"><b><a href="#cite_ref-47" title="">^</a></b> <cite style="font-style:normal" class="web"><a href="http://www.number10.gov.uk/output/Page7999.asp" class="external text" title="http://www.number10.gov.uk/output/Page7999.asp" rel="nofollow">"PM's Press Conference"</a>. <a href="/wiki/10_Downing_Street" title="10 Downing Street">10 Downing Street</a>. 26 July 2005<span class="printonly">. <a href="http://www.number10.gov.uk/output/Page7999.asp" class="external free" title="http://www.number10.gov.uk/output/Page7999.asp" rel="nofollow">http://www.number10.gov.uk/output/Page7999.asp</a></span><span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved on 2007-04-27</span>.</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=bookitem&amp;rft.btitle=PM%27s+Press+Conference&amp;rft.atitle=&amp;rft.date=26+July+2005&amp;rft.pub=%5B%5B10+Downing+Street%5D%5D&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.number10.gov.uk%2Foutput%2FPage7999.asp&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:American_and_British_English_differences"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span></li>
<li id="cite_note-48"><b><a href="#cite_ref-48" title="">^</a></b> <a href="http://www.bsa.org.uk/mediacentre/press/cheque_sept.htm" class="external text" title="http://www.bsa.org.uk/mediacentre/press/cheque_sept.htm" rel="nofollow">BSA changes to cheque writing</a> see end of numbered item 9</li>
<li id="cite_note-49"><b><a href="#cite_ref-49" title="">^</a></b> <a href="http://www.bsa.org.uk/mediacentre/press/cheque_sept.htm" class="external autonumber" title="http://www.bsa.org.uk/mediacentre/press/cheque_sept.htm" rel="nofollow">[6]</a> see end of numbered item 9</li>
<li id="cite_note-50"><b><a href="#cite_ref-50" title="">^</a></b> <cite style="font-style:normal" class="book" id="CITEREFStaff1996">Staff (1996). "American and British English". <i>The Economist Style Guide</i> (Fourth ed.). London: Hamish Hamilton Ltd. pp.&#160;85. <a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/0241135567" class="internal">ISBN 0241135567</a>.</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=bookitem&amp;rft.btitle=American+and+British+English&amp;rft.atitle=The+Economist+Style+Guide&amp;rft.aulast=Staff&amp;rft.au=Staff&amp;rft.date=1996&amp;rft.pages=pp.%26nbsp%3B85&amp;rft.edition=Fourth&amp;rft.place=London&amp;rft.pub=Hamish+Hamilton+Ltd&amp;rft.isbn=0241135567&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:American_and_British_English_differences"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span></li>
